<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Reflection</h2>



<p>I chose Thomas Hood&#8217;s &#8220;I Remember, I Remember&#8221; because of how musical it already seemed, especially with the repetition of &#8220;I remember&#8221; which made me hear a melody right away. The poem talks about nostalgia and losing childhood innocence, with each verse moving between hope and sadness. This back-and-forth gave me clear ideas for the music.</p>



<p>I started by figuring out the rhythm. The poem&#8217;s regular meter naturally lent itself to a 4/4 time signature. An early decision was to omit one stanza to keep the song to three minutes, but this actually helped make the piece more focused.</p>



<p>The melody came pretty naturally from the words, guided by the text&#8217;s natural rhythm and emotional content. I created the &#8220;I remember&#8221; descending motif to convey the hope-despair dichotomy present in the poem. Each stanza&#8217;s second half has a rising melodic line followed by a gradual descent, mirroring the poem&#8217;s emotional arc.</p>



<p>The hardest part was writing interesting piano music to go with the voice. Finding the right chords was easy enough, but making the piano part interesting was challenging. Given the text-heavy nature of the poem and the dominance of the melody, I kept the piano part simple, only adding more during the parts where the voice was silent.</p>



<p>In the harmony, I used diminished chords on D and F to add drama to the music. This helped bring out the emotional side of the poem. The way the melody goes up and then down in each verse really helped show the contrast between hope and sadness in the poem.</p>



<p>While I am particularly happy with the vocal melody, I acknowledge that the piano accompaniment remains somewhat conventional and could benefit from further development. Nonetheless, this assignment has helolped me understand the difficulty in text setting and the challenges in creating a unified piece from an existing poem. </p>
